If you're reading this, and you are/were a kid who went through childhood trauma due to neglect or any abusiveness from your parents. You are so incredibly strong and resilient, and I believe in you. Your days will only get brighter, and you're wonderful, and I'm glad you're here

It's in accepting faults and mistakes on their part and your own. It's the willingness to change. For them. For yourself. I have so much more that I think about in regards to this, but holy shit if I continue I might cry.

Nurture and care and love is more than the food you may or may not put on a child's plate. It is more than the roof they may or may not have over their heads. It's the commitment, the responsibility, the sincerity in every action and word. It's in cherish every moment.

Don't neglect and miss treat young kids and ask, "Why are you so awful to me? Why aren't you perfect?" I'm not saying everything a child does and acts is completely the parents fault, but I feel like most parents don't have the slightest idea how their choices affect their kids.

Does it ever occur to parents that one thing they say can stick with a child for the rest of their lives? That how they treat them influences how they treat others? It's insane! And I don't understand how she can have three children, struggle, and have more.

Yeah, the concept of building a family is cool, but do you have any idea the kind of commitment and responsibility you have to take on. Or how much damage you can do psychologically to a person by just how much you care and treat them?
